data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The **sync-over-async opt-in for the EF Core Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely** in EF Core 11. In .NET 10, you could configure `EnableSyncOverAsync()` to allow synchronous calls — that escape hatch no longer exists.

All four of your sync methods will throw **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime:

| Method | Throws | Async replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `ToList()` | ✅ | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | ✅ | `FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | ✅ | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | ✅ | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Fix — convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

This will cascade — every caller of these methods must also become `async/await` up the call chain. Start from the repository layer and work outward to controllers/services. ASP.NET Core controllers already support `async Task<IActionResult>` action methods, so the outermost layer typically requires minimal changes.
